article.headline: Golden Gophers never trailed
article.linkText: Minnesota rolls to seventh straight win
article.story:
SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Jamie Broback and Janel McCarville
took care of the scoring and Shannon Bolden spearheaded the
defense.

Broback scored 21 points and led No. 16 Minnesota to its seventh
straight win, a 69-42 victory over Santa Clara on Saturday.

McCarville added 17 points for the Golden Gophers (8-1) and
Shannon Schonrock made a pair of 3-pointers to move into third
place on Minnesota's career list with 121.

"The coach always tells us defense will win games for us,"
Broback said. "You don't always know if your shots will fall,
especially on the road."

Quinn Thomas scored 12 points to lead the Broncos (3-4), who
were held to their season low in points and shooting percentage (29
percent). Michelle Cozad had 10 points.

The Gophers are on pace to set the school record for scoring
defense set by last year's team at 59.7. They displayed their
defensive prowess by holding the Broncos 31 points under their
average.

"We wanted to take away their first looks," Broback said. "We
knew they were a good 3-point shooting team so we wanted to make
them go to their second and third options and they struggled with
that."

Bolden, who failed to score for the first time since an NCAA
tournament game against Texas in 2003, still contributed by holding
Santa Clara's leading scorer Ashley Graham scoreless.

"That's Shannon's role," Minnesota coach Pam Borton said.
"She defends the best guard or the leading scorer. She's still
coming back from an ankle sprain so she's not 100 percent. Right
now, if there's something she's going to sacrifice she'll give it
her all defensively."

Santa Clara, which was playing its third Top 25 team in 15 days,
entered play averaging a West Coast Conference best 73 points per
game.

"They got in us," Bronco Ashley Gonnerman said. "They had
intense defense all the way around. They never backed down and they
weren't afraid to get in our face. It's a great experience for us,
especially so early in the season. It shows our weaknesses."

Minnesota successfully pounded the ball inside against the
Broncos, with McCarville and Broback getting most of their points
in the paint. The Gophers outscored Santa Clara inside 26-13.
Minnesota held a 26-2 advantage at one point.

"We knew we had a mismatch in the post and any time we can
score in the paint we will," Borton said. "When Jamie is playing
against bigger players she can take them out to the perimeter, and
she can post up little guards. She's our most versatile player."

The Gophers never trailed, as Santa Clara missed six of its
first seven shots.

Minnesota made 14 of its first 21 shots and used a 19-2 run to
open a 22-point lead late in the first half. McCarville scored
eight points during the Gophers' run, in which the Broncos were
held scoreless for more than 6 minutes.

"I thought Minnesota came out in the beginning and set the tone
and took the wind away from us," Santa Clara coach Michelle
Bento-Jackson said. "We never really gained it back."

April Calhoun hit a driving layup with 8 seconds left in the
first half to give Minnesota a 40-19 lead.

The Gophers were making their first trip to California since
reaching the Sweet 16 in 2003 at Stanford. Minnesota won the Santa
Clara Shootout in 1992.
